They don’t tell you how strong you must be to go thru the postpartum stage. Your emotions are all out of whack, you barely sleep & you have a new little one that solely relies on you. You have to feed your body constantly just to supplement your milk that actually never came in, you’re feeding every 3 hours & somewhere throughout the day, you just want to take a long hot shower. You’re in diapers for a couple weeks just healing & the sleepless nights are the worst, you try everything to help calm baby down but nothing works and you start feeling like you’re not cut out for this. I’m 5-weeks postpartum and I’m finally getting into a routine. I’m back at the salon a couple days a week to help me just get away from the four walls of my home. My husband & I have a “decent” routine 😂 & my mom has helped… a lot. After talking to other moms, it’s ok to feel like this. The sleepless nights will minimize & you’ll be able to look at your child & feel the adoration he has for you.

Just letting y’all know, I feel your struggle & I promise… IT WILL GET EASIER… but I wouldn’t trade this for anything.

My sister in law is a professional maternity photographer. I watched her kick off her career and grow exponentially throughout the last decade. Her and I would sit in her studio late at night and talk about the different techniques she was incorporating and new props or dresses she was trying. I loved witnessing her evolve in this art form, her resiliency, her hustle and her passion for it. I looked forward to sharing the maternity and newborn experience with her when the time was right but then infertility happened and I feared our chance wouldn’t come. Many years and prayers later, and our chance arrived. 

Glenda looks at photos from a bigger picture. They aren’t just for show, but are a lifetime memory for yourself and generations to come and cherish. She has this skill of making you feel at ease and beautiful during the whole session, sparking confidence and joy. 

Thank you for this lifelong gift, @glendaphotography
